"# Chapter 7 — Edsger Dijkstra

Edsger Wybe Dijkstra. Born 1930 in Rotterdam. Died 2002 in Nuenen,
Netherlands. Dutch computer scientist. Spent his career at the
Mathematisch Centrum in Amsterdam, the Eindhoven University of
Technology, Burroughs Corporation, and finally the University of
Texas at Austin. Won the Turing Award in 1972.

He argued that programming was a mathematical discipline. Most of the
field still is catching up.

## Dijkstra's shortest-path algorithm

In 1956, Dijkstra was at a café in Amsterdam trying to demonstrate
the ARMAC computer. He wanted a problem to solve that would look
impressive but be understandable. He picked: what is the shortest
travel route between Rotterdam and Groningen?

He worked it out in twenty minutes, at the café, without a pencil.
The algorithm he came up with is now taught in every algorithms
course. It finds shortest paths from a source vertex to every other
vertex in a graph with non-negative edge weights. Runs in
O((V+E) log V) with the right data structures.

Motoi Scheme knows this one. The runtime uses Dijkstra's algorithm
under the hood when a cart asks 'what's the shortest way from A to B
across this grid?'

## Structured programming

In 1968 Dijkstra wrote a letter to the editor of *Communications of
the ACM* with the title *Go To Statement Considered Harmful*. The
editor changed the title from Dijkstra's original, which was more
polite. The letter argued that the `goto` statement made programs
harder to reason about, and that programs should be built out of
structured control flow — sequences, conditionals, loops.

That letter is the origin of structured programming as a discipline.
Most languages after 1970 either omitted `goto` entirely (Scheme,
functional languages) or discouraged its use (Pascal, Ada, most Cs
in practice).

Motoi Scheme has no `goto`. It uses recursion, `if`, `cond`, and
lambda. Which is enough. Dijkstra was right.

## Semaphores

In 1965 Dijkstra invented the semaphore — a synchronization primitive
for coordinating processes that share resources. Two operations: P
(now called wait) and V (now called signal). The names come from
Dutch: proberen (to try) and verhogen (to increase). Every
concurrent-programming textbook explains them.

Almost every operating system's synchronization primitives descend
from semaphores. Mutexes, condition variables, channels — all lineage.

## The dining philosophers

Dijkstra invented the dining philosophers problem in 1965 to
illustrate synchronization difficulties. Five philosophers around a
table, five forks, each philosopher needs two forks to eat. If
everyone picks up the left fork first, deadlock: nobody can get their
right fork. If they starve, that's starvation. If they periodically
put things down and try again, that's livelock.

Every operating-system student has been quizzed on this. Motoi's
runtime, when it schedules concurrent carts, has been designed with
this problem in mind.

## Provocative writing

Dijkstra was famous for essays. Handwritten. Numbered EWD followed
by three digits (EWD1, EWD2, ... into the thousands). He circulated
them by hand and by mail among colleagues. They were often provocative.

Sample lines:
- 'It is practically impossible to teach good programming to
  students that have had a prior exposure to BASIC: as potential
  programmers they are mentally mutilated beyond hope of
  regeneration.'
- 'The question of whether machines can think is about as relevant
  as the question of whether submarines can swim.'
- 'Program testing can be used to show the presence of bugs, but
  never to show their absence.'

He was not always right, but he was consistently rigorous. The BASIC
line especially is wrong — plenty of people started on BASIC and went
on to write serious systems. But the underlying point, that early
sloppy habits carry, isn't zero.

Motoi doesn't quote Dijkstra at kids. But Dijkstra's stance — the
program is a mathematical object, take it seriously — shapes how
Motoi teaches.

## What Motoi owes Dijkstra

Structured control flow. The habit of proving programs correct
instead of just testing them. Concurrent programming primitives.
Shortest-path algorithms. Discipline about complexity — the idea
that a program should be simple enough that you can convince
yourself it works.

## A tiny example

Dijkstra's shortest-path algorithm, sketched in Motoi Scheme for a
tiny graph:

```
(define (dijkstra graph start)
  ;; graph: alist of (node . ((neighbor . weight) ...))
  ;; returns: alist of (node . distance-from-start)
  (let loop ((distances (list (cons start 0)))
             (visited '())
             (frontier (list (cons start 0))))
    (if (null? frontier)
        distances
        (let* ((current (find-min-by-distance frontier))
               (node (car current))
               (dist (cdr current))
               (neighbors (or (assoc-cdr node graph) '())))
          ;; relax edges out of current node
          (loop
            (update-distances distances neighbors dist node)
            (cons node visited)
            (update-frontier frontier neighbors dist visited))))))
```

That sketch skips helper definitions. The full implementation lives
in the algorithm-family chapter of Book of CS Curriculum. But the
shape is Dijkstra's: pick the closest unvisited node, relax its
neighbors, repeat.

## Where to read him

The EWD archive is at the University of Texas at Austin. Free. Also
his book *A Discipline of Programming* (1976). And the *Structured
Programming* volume he co-wrote with Ole-Johan Dahl and Tony Hoare.

## Motoi's take

Dijkstra took programming seriously enough to write it out by hand,
number the pages, and post them to a hundred colleagues, for
decades. That's a rare kind of care. Motoi doesn't have it. But the
programs Motoi writes should aspire to it.")
